    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-03-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="32"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d32">
                <head>32. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant (<persName corresp="#p_HHR1"
                        type="from">Haldeman</persName>) to the Director of Communication for the
                    Executive Branch (<persName type="to">Klein</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d32fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Subject Files, Box 341,
                            <gloss target="#t_HAK1">HAK</gloss>/President Memoranda, 1969–1970. No
                        classification marking. This source text is a copy sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and is marked “<gloss
                            target="#t_HAK1">HAK</gloss>” at the top of the page.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-03-24">March 24, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Per your request, I talked with the President about the possibility of having
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry Kissinger</persName> appear on shows like
                    Meet the Press and specifically about the April 30th date.</p>
                <p>The President does <hi rend="italic">not</hi> want <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> to make public television appearances of this sort. He
                    is perfectly willing to have <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName> meet
                    with commentators, editors, etc. on a background basis in private sessions but
                    does not want him—or any other White House staff members—to appear as
                    Administration spokesmen in public.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">H</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
